There is no contradiction, the \"claim to elucidate the level of free will\" concerns the earthly judges, who do not have the means and adequate knowledge for this. Whereas on Ummo they do, but they dispense with it when judging.

The amusing contradiction is that ignoring that there is a (rather limited) degree of freedom, and all the psychic process at work in the acts, makes it 1) cruel to judge an act as if it were totally free, and 2) allows for a reduction of the sentence when it is declared involuntary.

To get out of these excesses one must be aware that more powerful punishments than one can imagine are inflicted by BB after death, and that the search for justice can only be based on an understanding of educational mechanisms.

The thing I note is that these action-reward learning principles can easily get twisted, in that when crime is rewarded (e.g. health business) then the torturer always seeks to punish good deeds...

And where well-rewarded good deeds always command respect, the former are always desperate to get it, even if it means force.
And by a curious twist, imposing adulation inspires disgust, just as exemplarity produces the effect of a reward for those who want to emulate it: we are always in the action-reward pattern.

I had the pleasure of re-reading this with yet another new eye.
I thought there must be a way to modulate this unconscious pressure, which is what you do when you are inspired by someone.

The fact that this flow of information is rigid and deterministic, and ultimately all subsequent processes up to action, places free will as a filter, as the initiator of this process, or simply unable to act as the case may be. Elucidating this question must be a matter of high science, philosophy and spirituality.

